1
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:54,799
A plane.

2
00:01:12,319 --> 00:01:14,159
A foreign air force plane.

3
00:01:14,879 --> 00:01:16,120
How did it end up here?

4
00:01:16,799 --> 00:01:18,400
Looks like it's been here for years.

5
00:01:19,040 --> 00:01:20,319
Could it be from the 1940s?

6
00:01:20,319 --> 00:01:21,799
The Flying Tigers that aided China?

7
00:01:22,560 --> 00:01:23,680
The Flying Tigers should have

8
00:01:23,680 --> 00:01:25,400
flight formation markings.

9
00:01:26,959 --> 00:01:27,719
It's been too long.

10
00:01:27,719 --> 00:01:28,799
They must have weathered away.

11
00:01:29,079 --> 00:01:30,200
Probably can't see them clearly anymore.

12
00:01:31,159 --> 00:01:31,959
Maybe.

13
00:01:34,079 --> 00:01:35,599
We're pretty close to the border here.

14
00:01:35,599 --> 00:01:36,799
There were reports before

15
00:01:37,239 --> 00:01:38,640
saying that around the Nujiang Grand Canyon

16
00:01:38,640 --> 00:01:40,480
and the Gaoligong Mountains near here,

17
00:01:40,719 --> 00:01:41,879
they did find dozens of

18
00:01:41,879 --> 00:01:43,159
foreign aircraft wreckages.

19
00:01:43,159 --> 00:01:44,840
Old Chen, Staff Officer He,

20
00:01:44,840 --> 00:01:46,319
why is it so quiet up there?

21
00:01:46,959 --> 00:01:48,719
We found a plane.

22
00:01:50,599 --> 00:01:51,599
A plane?

23
00:01:51,879 --> 00:01:53,519
Why is there a plane in the tree?

24
00:01:58,280 --> 00:01:59,079
Listen.

25
00:02:06,319 --> 00:02:07,519
It's been so many years.

26
00:02:08,080 --> 00:02:09,560
There can't be any survivors, right?

27
00:02:10,319 --> 00:02:11,159
Let's go take a look.

28
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:12,759
I'll go first.

29
00:02:23,879 --> 00:02:24,479
Don't move.

30
00:02:26,120 --> 00:02:27,439
Even though this canopy is big enough,

31
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:30,120
the trunk isn't as sturdy as we thought.

32
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:31,879
Plus the weight of the plane,

33
00:02:32,280 --> 00:02:33,240
we need to be careful.

34
00:02:33,840 --> 00:02:34,680
You stay here.

35
00:02:35,159 --> 00:02:36,120
I'll go take a look.

36
00:03:42,439 --> 00:03:43,120
It's nothing.

37
00:03:43,680 --> 00:03:44,879
Just a skeleton.

38
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:29,279
Look.

39
00:04:52,240 --> 00:04:53,560
Something flew out.

40
00:04:54,600 --> 00:04:55,720
I spotted a bird.

41
00:04:56,240 --> 00:04:57,519
Why is the bird so big?

42
00:04:59,600 --> 00:05:00,639
It's a Eurasian eagle-owl.

43
00:05:01,560 --> 00:05:02,360
A Eurasian eagle-owl?

44
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:05,279
Don't Eurasian eagle-owls nest on cliffs?

45
00:05:05,519 --> 00:05:06,560
Why is it here?

46
00:05:07,079 --> 00:05:07,879
I don't know.

47
00:05:08,600 --> 00:05:10,079
I've seen them in the Northeast before.

48
00:05:10,680 --> 00:05:12,759
Golden eyes, sharp beak and claws.

49
00:05:13,279 --> 00:05:14,439
One swipe of its claws

50
00:05:14,439 --> 00:05:16,160
can tear off a huge chunk of a black bear's skin.

51
00:05:17,439 --> 00:05:18,279
Its nest is here.

52
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:19,160
It'll probably come back.

53
00:05:19,160 --> 00:05:20,040
Let's hurry up.

54
00:05:20,040 --> 00:05:20,680
Okay.

55
00:05:22,040 --> 00:05:24,079
Old Chen, be careful!

56
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:34,279
What are you looking at? You're too heavy.

57
00:05:39,800 --> 00:05:40,480
Look.

58
00:05:41,680 --> 00:05:43,120
There seems to be an ammo box here.

59
00:05:46,480 --> 00:05:47,279
You hold this.

60
00:06:03,279 --> 00:06:04,279
So many bullets.

61
00:06:04,600 --> 00:06:05,000
Yeah.

62
00:06:05,000 --> 00:06:05,920
What do they go into?

63
00:06:20,920 --> 00:06:22,680
A Thompson submachine gun.

64
00:06:22,879 --> 00:06:24,160
Now we have something for self-defense.

65
00:06:24,160 --> 00:06:25,600
Can it still be used after so many years?

66
00:06:26,959 --> 00:06:27,639
No problem.

67
00:06:28,480 --> 00:06:29,199
Fatty!

68
00:06:30,279 --> 00:06:31,720
I'm throwing down something good for you!

69
00:06:32,199 --> 00:06:33,360
What good thing?

70
00:06:37,240 --> 00:06:37,920
Watch out!

71
00:06:40,920 --> 00:06:41,879
Brother Pang, watch out!

72
00:06:44,879 --> 00:06:45,560
What's wrong?

73
00:06:46,160 --> 00:06:46,920
A rock!

74
00:06:47,480 --> 00:06:48,240
That's the Eurasian eagle-owl.

75
00:06:48,759 --> 00:06:49,920
It's highly aggressive.

76
00:06:51,199 --> 00:06:54,720
Old Chen, up there is that... that eagle...

77
00:06:55,279 --> 00:06:56,319
Eurasian eagle-owl.

78
00:06:56,439 --> 00:06:57,160
Right, right, right.

79
00:06:57,319 --> 00:06:59,120
Come down quickly! It's dangerous!

80
00:07:00,439 --> 00:07:01,480
It's back again.

81
00:07:03,439 --> 00:07:04,240
Fatty!

82
00:07:04,439 --> 00:07:06,120
I'm throwing the Thompson submachine gun down to you!

83
00:07:06,399 --> 00:07:07,680
Catch it and wait for my command!

84
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:08,319
Okay!

85
00:07:08,560 --> 00:07:09,920
There are bullets in the magazine!

86
00:07:18,600 --> 00:07:19,720
It's the real deal,

87
00:07:19,800 --> 00:07:20,920
a Chicago Typewriter!

88
00:07:26,639 --> 00:07:27,279
Fatty!

89
00:07:27,680 --> 00:07:28,519
Wait for my command!

90
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:29,920
Using the tent as a reference,

91
00:07:38,759 --> 00:07:39,759
eleven o'clock!

92
00:07:55,720 --> 00:07:56,519
Nine o'clock!

93
00:08:06,480 --> 00:08:07,519
Twelve o'clock!

94
00:08:29,680 --> 00:08:30,600
I say, Commander Chen,

95
00:08:31,120 --> 00:08:32,519
I've turned almost half a circle.

96
00:08:32,759 --> 00:08:33,799
This tree is too big.

97
00:08:33,799 --> 00:08:34,919
I can't hit anything!

98
00:08:35,159 --> 00:08:35,799
Take cover!

99
00:08:54,559 --> 00:08:55,440
Take cover! Take cover!

100
00:08:55,440 --> 00:08:55,799
Go, go, go!

101
00:08:55,799 --> 00:08:56,240
Go!

102
00:08:59,600 --> 00:09:01,080
Fatty! Fatty!

103
00:09:01,639 --> 00:09:02,360
Be careful!

104
00:09:03,519 --> 00:09:04,519
Watch out!

105
00:09:05,399 --> 00:09:06,759
What are you yelling about?

106
00:09:15,519 --> 00:09:16,200
Where is he?

107
00:09:23,600 --> 00:09:24,120
Brother Fatty!

108
00:09:24,120 --> 00:09:25,399
They're all up in the canopy!

109
00:09:25,399 --> 00:09:26,919
Fall... Fall back! Fall back and shoot!

110
00:09:27,039 --> 00:09:28,039
Hurry, hurry, hurry!

111
00:09:38,679 --> 00:09:39,559
You're just getting in the way!

112
00:09:40,840 --> 00:09:41,720
Are you okay?

113
00:09:41,919 --> 00:09:43,519
Okay my ass! How could I be okay?

114
00:09:43,919 --> 00:09:44,799
What are you doing here?

115
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:46,720
Helping out!

116
00:09:47,799 --> 00:09:48,320
Alright, alright.

117
00:09:48,320 --> 00:09:49,279
Just protect yourself,

118
00:09:49,279 --> 00:09:50,320
and that'll be helping out enough!

119
00:09:50,440 --> 00:09:51,000
Just stay out of the way!

120
00:09:51,000 --> 00:09:52,080
This is peach wood!

121
00:09:52,080 --> 00:09:52,480
Move!

122
00:09:52,480 --> 00:09:53,320
Peach wood!

123
00:09:55,080 --> 00:09:56,120
Ten o'clock!

124
00:10:02,000 --> 00:10:02,919
Six o'clock!

125
00:10:04,879 --> 00:10:05,519
Take cover!

126
00:10:12,919 --> 00:10:14,120
Looks like they all flew away.

127
00:10:20,960 --> 00:10:22,159
What's going on?

128
00:10:22,360 --> 00:10:23,759
The plane seems to be moving!

129
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:26,320
Is it because you're too heavy?

130
00:10:26,320 --> 00:10:27,120
How can you say that?

131
00:10:27,639 --> 00:10:29,120
It's clearly tilting towards your side!

132
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:37,720
Go!

133
00:11:00,320 --> 00:11:00,960
Run!

134
00:11:22,279 --> 00:11:24,080
Fatty, are you okay?

135
00:11:24,159 --> 00:11:25,799
He's fine! He's fine!

136
00:11:36,120 --> 00:11:36,840
Brother Pang,

137
00:11:37,200 --> 00:11:39,399
it looks like an airplane.

138
00:11:40,279 --> 00:11:41,039
Lord Pang,

139
00:11:41,840 --> 00:11:43,320
you're really something this time.

140
00:11:44,120 --> 00:11:45,159
Others shoot big birds,

141
00:11:45,679 --> 00:11:47,320
but you shot down this thing.

142
00:11:48,759 --> 00:11:49,960
I don't care what it is.

143
00:11:50,240 --> 00:11:51,919
They both have wings anyway.

144
00:11:52,159 --> 00:11:53,360
Shooting it was the right call.

145
00:11:59,480 --> 00:12:00,120
Old Chen,

146
00:12:00,759 --> 00:12:01,440
are you okay?

147
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:02,600
I'm fine.

148
00:12:04,039 --> 00:12:04,720
Brother,

149
00:12:04,840 --> 00:12:06,360
what was that distress signal about?

150
00:12:06,360 --> 00:12:08,519
And where did this plane come from?

151
00:12:08,720 --> 00:12:09,360
That distress signal

152
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:10,600
was from a Eurasian eagle-owl nesting in the cabin.

153
00:12:10,600 --> 00:12:11,519
It made that sound.

154
00:12:12,039 --> 00:12:13,000
We don't know about the plane either.

155
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:14,519
It was at the top when we climbed the tree.

156
00:12:14,639 --> 00:12:16,000
Look at you all.

157
00:12:16,799 --> 00:12:18,480
You're just being paranoid.

158
00:12:18,919 --> 00:12:20,600
A big bird builds a nest,

159
00:12:20,600 --> 00:12:22,120
and you insist it's Morse code.

160
00:12:22,120 --> 00:12:23,399
If the big bird laid an egg,

161
00:12:23,399 --> 00:12:25,360
you'd probably say it's an atomic bomb explosion.

162
00:12:26,600 --> 00:12:27,240
Brother!

163
00:12:27,799 --> 00:12:28,519
What are you yelling for?

164
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:29,960
Just talking to yourself.

165
00:12:30,159 --> 00:12:31,559
This... This...

166
00:12:31,879 --> 00:12:33,360
This is really a foreign plane.

167
00:12:33,919 --> 00:12:36,279
Its serial number is 457...

168
00:12:36,960 --> 00:12:37,759
One digit is unclear...

169
00:12:37,759 --> 00:12:38,799
The last digit is 4.

170
00:12:39,639 --> 00:12:41,279
This should be a plane from the 1940s

171
00:12:41,559 --> 00:12:43,279
that disappeared in the Bermuda waters,

172
00:12:43,279 --> 00:12:46,799
one of the Flight 19 fleet.

173
00:12:47,720 --> 00:12:49,320
And it ended up resting on a big tree?

174
00:12:50,000 --> 00:12:51,440
What is the meaning of this?

175
00:12:51,720 --> 00:12:52,639
Are you sure?

176
00:12:52,879 --> 00:12:54,240
When I was in school,

177
00:12:54,519 --> 00:12:55,879
I read a magazine that specifically compiled

178
00:12:55,960 --> 00:12:57,519
supernatural events in Bermuda.

179
00:12:58,080 --> 00:12:59,320
It was in the 1940s,

180
00:12:59,600 --> 00:13:01,159
five foreign military planes

181
00:13:01,159 --> 00:13:03,039
took off from Fort Lorenzo, Florida,

182
00:13:03,080 --> 00:13:04,519
to carry out a maritime training mission.

183
00:13:05,080 --> 00:13:06,799
They all disappeared in the Bermuda waters.

184
00:13:07,559 --> 00:13:11,639
The serial number of one of them was 45714.

185
00:13:14,159 --> 00:13:16,240
Isn't the serial number of this plane incomplete?

186
00:13:16,279 --> 00:13:17,600
It might not necessarily be that one.

187
00:13:17,600 --> 00:13:18,919
I thought about that too just now.

188
00:13:19,480 --> 00:13:22,600
But the model of this plane is TBM.

189
00:13:22,799 --> 00:13:24,039
The model of the missing plane

190
00:13:24,039 --> 00:13:25,480
was also a TBM Avenger.

191
00:13:25,799 --> 00:13:26,840
And for this serial number,

192
00:13:26,960 --> 00:13:28,399
only one digit is unclear.

193
00:13:28,600 --> 00:13:31,919
Ber... Bermuda's big plane?

194
00:13:33,320 --> 00:13:34,320
I know about this.

195
00:13:34,720 --> 00:13:36,240
It's the legendary

196
00:13:36,399 --> 00:13:37,720
Gate to Hell, right?

197
00:13:37,799 --> 00:13:38,639
Right, right, right.

198
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:40,440
This area of the sea

199
00:13:40,679 --> 00:13:42,600
is often haunted by supernatural events.

200
00:13:42,840 --> 00:13:45,440
But Bermuda is nowhere near here.

201
00:13:45,440 --> 00:13:48,080
These two places are poles apart.

202
00:14:11,679 --> 00:14:13,720
Master Chen, didn't you just say

203
00:14:13,720 --> 00:14:16,320
this sound was made by a big bird nesting?

204
00:14:16,799 --> 00:14:18,000
I've already scared the bird away.

205
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:19,240
Why is the sound still there?

206
00:14:23,120 --> 00:14:23,919
Staff Officer He,

207
00:14:24,679 --> 00:14:26,000
listen to what that is.

208
00:14:30,080 --> 00:14:32,679
Cold. Dark.

209
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:35,639
What does that mean?

210
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:40,279
It means cold and dark.

211
00:14:48,039 --> 00:14:48,720
What's wrong?

212
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:51,120
We are in Nanyun, right?

213
00:14:53,159 --> 00:14:54,440
The kid is scared silly.

214
00:14:54,559 --> 00:14:55,799
If this isn't Nanyun, where is it?

215
00:14:55,960 --> 00:14:57,600
B-But what I measured...

216
00:14:57,840 --> 00:14:59,440
The geographical coordinates of this tree are

217
00:15:00,159 --> 00:15:03,639
20 degrees North latitude, 75 degrees West longitude.

218
00:15:05,960 --> 00:15:08,039
No, w-what does that mean?

219
00:15:08,799 --> 00:15:12,399
These coordinates belong to the Bermuda Triangle.

220
00:15:17,000 --> 00:15:18,240
I've measured it three times.

221
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:19,840
Same answer.

222
00:15:30,879 --> 00:15:33,360
Th-This sound...

223
00:15:34,600 --> 00:15:36,320
Could it really be coming from

224
00:15:39,879 --> 00:15:40,879
hell?
